# Agent Context

**Version:** 3.0.0

This repository is the **base agent skill package** -- compatible with Windsurf, Devin, and other AI coding agents.

<!-- ASP:agent-detection:BEGIN -->
## Agent Detection

This setup supports multiple AI coding tools. Each agent should use its native integration:

- **Windsurf Cascade**: Rules auto-apply from `.windsurf/rules/`. Trigger workflows via `/workflow-name`.
- **Devin**: Rules auto-apply from `.windsurf/rules/` (read via compatibility layer). Use skills from `.devin/skills/` to execute workflows. Skills wrap the same workflow definitions.
- **Cursor / Other agents**: Read `.windsurf/rules/` for behavioral rules. For workflows, read `.windsurf/workflows/<name>.md` and execute the steps described there.
<!-- ASP:agent-detection:END -->

<!-- ASP:purpose:BEGIN -->
## Purpose

Drop `.windsurf/` and `.devin/` into any project to get a fully configured AI agent baseline. Rules are active immediately -- no configuration required. The `AGENTS.md` is created or merged automatically by the installer.

All behavioral rules (identity, language, communication style) are defined in `.windsurf/rules/global-agent.md` -- this file provides project context only, not duplicated behavior instructions.
<!-- ASP:purpose:END -->

<!-- ASP:how-to-initialize:BEGIN -->
## How to Initialize a New Project

### Instant (no setup)

1. Copy `.windsurf/` and `.devin/` into the target project root
2. Run `.windsurf/tools/install.bat` (Windows) or `.windsurf/tools/install.sh` (macOS/Linux) -- this creates or merges `AGENTS.md` automatically
3. Open in your AI coding tool -- rules are active immediately

### With Stack-Specific Rules

#### Windsurf

1. Copy `.windsurf/` and `.devin/` into the target project root
2. Run `.windsurf/tools/install.bat` (Windows) or `.windsurf/tools/install.sh` (macOS/Linux)
3. Click "Analyze Project" in the UI to auto-detect your stack, or fill in manually
4. Click "Save & Generate" -- `AGENTS.md` is created or merged automatically
5. Run `/project-init` in Windsurf -- the agent generates stack-specific rules automatically

#### Devin

1. Copy `.windsurf/` and `.devin/` into the target project root
2. Start the config server: `node .windsurf/tools/config-server.js`
3. Run analysis via API: `curl http://localhost:3847/analyze`
4. Save config via API: `curl -X POST http://localhost:3847/save-config -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d '<config JSON>'` -- `AGENTS.md` is created or merged automatically
5. Invoke the `project-init` skill -- Devin executes all 4 phases automatically
<!-- ASP:how-to-initialize:END -->

<!-- ASP:merge-strategy:BEGIN -->
## AGENTS.md Merge Strategy

When this package is installed into a project that already has an `AGENTS.md`, a smart merge preserves both the project-specific content and the ASP-managed sections.

### How It Works

All ASP-managed content is wrapped in HTML comment markers: `<!-- ASP:section-name:BEGIN -->` / `<!-- ASP:section-name:END -->`. Content outside these markers is project-specific and never touched by the merge.

### Merge Scenarios

| Scenario | Action | Backup |
| --- | --- | --- |
| No existing `AGENTS.md` | Full template created | No |
| Existing file **with** ASP markers (re-run) | ASP sections updated in-place, project content preserved | Yes |
| Existing file **without** ASP markers (first install) | Project content wrapped under "Project-Specific Documentation", ASP sections appended | Yes |

### When Does It Run

- **Automatically** during `/save-config` (when saving tech stack configuration)
- **Manually** via API: `curl http://localhost:3847/merge-agents-md`
- **Status check** via API: `curl http://localhost:3847/agents-md-status`

### Merge Modes (via POST /merge-agents-md)

| Mode | Behavior |
| --- | --- |
| `merge` (default) | Smart merge: preserve project content, update ASP sections |
| `overwrite` | Replace entirely with template (backup created) |
| `skip` | Do nothing |

### Backups

Backups are stored in `.windsurf/backups/AGENTS.md.<timestamp>.backup` before any modification.
<!-- ASP:merge-strategy:END -->

<!-- ASP:active-rules:BEGIN -->
## Active Rules

All files in `.windsurf/rules/` are auto-applied based on their `trigger` mode:

- `global-agent.md` -- always active (identity, language, communication style)
- `plan-first.md` -- model decision (structured change plan before multi-file edits)
- `code-quality.md` -- active for `.ts`, `.tsx`, `.js`, `.jsx`, `.py`, `.cs`, `.java`, `.kt`, `.go`, `.rs`, `.php`, `.rb`, `.ex`, `.scala`, `.dart`
- `security.md` -- active for `.ts`, `.tsx`, `.js`, `.py`, `.cs`, `.go`, `.rs`
- `error-handling.md` -- active for `.ts`, `.tsx`, `.js`, `.py`, `.cs`, `.go`, `.rs`
- `performance.md` -- active for `.ts`, `.tsx`, `.js`, `.py`, `.cs`, `.go`, `.rs`
- `accessibility.md` -- active for `.tsx`, `.jsx`, `.html`, `.vue`, `.svelte`
- `api-standards.md` -- active for `.ts`, `.py`, `.cs`, `.go`, `.rs`, `.java`, `.kt`, `.php`, `.rb`, `.ex`
- `i18n.md` -- active for `.tsx`, `.jsx`, `.ts`, `.py`, `.vue`, `.svelte`
- `testing.md` -- active for test files (`*.test.ts`, `*.spec.ts`, `test_*.py`, `*_test.go`, `*_test.rs`)
<!-- ASP:active-rules:END -->

